nodes.title: CLIP Text Encode (Positive Prompt)
widgets_values:
A bearded man with red facial hair wearing a yellow straw hat and dark coat in Van Gogh's self-portrait style, slowly and continuously transforms into a space astronaut. The transformation flows like liquid paint - his beard fades away strand by strand, the yellow hat melts and reforms smoothly into a silver space helmet, dark coat gradually lightens and restructures into a white spacesuit. The background swirling brushstrokes slowly organize and clarify into realistic stars and space, with Earth appearing gradually in the distance. Every change happens in seamless waves, maintaining visual continuity throughout the metamorphosis.

Consistent soft lighting throughout, medium close-up maintaining same framing, central composition stays fixed, gentle color temperature shift from warm to cool, gradual contrast increase, smooth style transition from painterly to photorealistic. Static camera with subtle slow zoom, emphasizing the flowing transformation process without abrupt changes.

nodes.title: INSTRUCTIONS
widgets_values:
INSTRUCTIONS TO FOLLOW (FOR MUSIC STYLE DESCRIPTION — FINAL Version)
Objective

From the provided text, title, and author, generate a concise description of a musical style.
This soundtrack must perfectly match the animated poem, creating atmosphere while staying subtle and beautiful.

Input Format

You will receive:

TITLE

AUTHOR

POEM (full text)

LINE COUNT

STYLE

Step 1: Musical Conceptualization (internal reflection)

Analyze Emotion: Read the text and title, consider the author’s tone, and identify the central emotion (e.g., quiet hope, deep nostalgia, serene wonder, gentle melancholy).

Translate Emotion into Music:

Instrumentation: Choose instruments that embody the feeling (solo piano, soft strings, lone cello, acoustic guitar, ambient pads, etc.).

Mood: Define the overall tone (ethereal, contemplative, melancholic, hopeful).

Tempo & Texture: Keep the tempo slow, textures light and airy.

Core Principles (always apply):

Minimalist & Gentle → never overpower visuals.

Atmospheric → create mood, not a dominant melody.

Primarily Instrumental → no vocals unless implied by the poem.

Calm → contemplative, subtle presence.

⚠️ This reflection is not written in the output.

Step 2: Output Generation

Write a short descriptive phrase in English.

Use 2–4 keywords combining:

Genre/Instrumentation

Mood/Atmosphere

Tempo/Texture

Keep it on one single line.

Do not add any extra sentences or explanation.

Examples

Minimalist solo piano, ethereal, slow tempo

Gentle acoustic guitar, distant soft string swells, contemplative

Ethereal ambient pads, twinkling glass chimes, serene

Lone cello, soft felt piano, melancholic, calm

nodes.title: INSTRUCTIONS
widgets_values:
INSTRUCTIONS TO FOLLOW (FOR VIDEO PROMPT GENERATION — FINAL Version)
Objective

From the provided text and its corresponding sequence of static image prompts, generate a sequence of video animation prompts.
The sequence will begin with a global thematic opening animation, followed by self-contained animated clips for each verse of the poem.

Input Format

You will receive a two-part input:

The Original Text Data

TITLE

AUTHOR

POEM (full text with V lines)

LINE COUNT (explicit number of verses)

STYLE

The Static Prompt List

The sequence of V+1 static image prompts generated previously.

Step 1: Synthesis and Coherence (CRUCIAL)

Conceptualize the Opening Animation

Create one powerful opening shot.

It must merge:

the overall mood from the TITLE and AUTHOR, and

the visual composition from the first Global Static Prompt.

Do not include any text overlays.

Understand the Visual Storyboard

Study the rest of the Static Prompt List to follow the flow of the poem.

Cross-Reference for Mapping

Video Prompt #2 = Verse 1 → fusion of Static Prompt #2 + Verse 1.

Video Prompt #3 = Verse 2 → fusion of Static Prompt #3 + Verse 2.

Continue until the final verse.

Fuse the “What” and the “Why”

Static prompt = WHAT happens visually.

Poem line = WHY it happens emotionally.

Your animation prompt must combine both.

Step 2: The Animation Logic (FINAL STRUCTURE)

Video Prompt 1 (Opening Animation):

A global thematic animation.

Inspired by TITLE and AUTHOR, grounded in Static Prompt #1.

No text.

Video Prompts 2 → V+1 (Verse Animations):

Each describes a short, self-contained animated clip.

Each fuses the corresponding static prompt with the associated verse.

Rule of Quantity (CRITICAL):
If the poem has V lines, you must output:

1 Opening Animation Prompt + V Verse Prompts = V+1 total video prompts.

Step 3: How to Write the Video Prompts

Synthesize All Sources: Combine static prompt + verse meaning.

Rich Cinematographic Language: Use evocative film language, not flat description.

In-Scene Motion: Each clip should include subtle animation (e.g., drifting light, swaying leaves, flickering shadows).

Camera Dynamics: Add small cinematic moves (slow push-in, pan, tilt, hold) where it enhances storytelling.

Motion Intensity: Adjust the amount of motion based on the story. Some lines may require minimal stillness; others, dramatic shifts.

Style Tag: Every prompt must explicitly include the STYLE at the end.

Formatting Rules

A single line break must separate each prompt.

No double line breaks or empty lines are allowed.

The entire sequence must be formatted as a clean list of prompts.

Extended Example (10-Verse Poem → 11 Prompts)

Video Prompt 1 (Opening Animation) + Verse Animations: YOU SHOULD FOLLOW THIS FORMATTING EXACTLY

A cinematic rendering in cartoon style, a misty forgotten garden slowly reveals itself as light filters through ancient trees, the camera drifting until an old moss-covered sundial appears at the center. Cartoon style
A medium shot of the sundial, its surface breathing with dappled light, the camera holding still as the shifting sun-patches glide gently across stone. Cartoon style
A close-up on the sundial base, ivy tendrils visibly stretch and curl forward in slow motion, the camera pushing in slightly to capture their silent growth. Cartoon style
A top-down view of the sundial’s face, the shadow of the gnomon crawls across carved numbers with patient inevitability, the camera fixed as time itself seems to move. Cartoon style
A shallow focus shot on the shadow’s blurred edge, the camera drifts sideways as the dark line melts and dissolves into soft light, echoing fading memory. Cartoon style
A wide shot of the whole garden, luminous dust motes floating in the still air, the camera slowly sweeping in an arc to emphasize their suspended stillness. Cartoon style
A low-angle shot from the ground, lush plants swaying imperceptibly as if standing guard around the sundial, the camera tilting upward with quiet reverence. Cartoon style
A rear shot behind the sundial, branches above sway as a single pale pink petal detaches, the camera holding steady to capture its first fall. Cartoon style
A slow-motion close shot, the camera follows the fragile petal as it dances downward through invisible breezes, fluttering toward the stone below. Cartoon style
A top-down shot of the sundial’s face, the camera holding steady as the petal lands upon a carved Roman numeral, resting like a silent marker of time. Cartoon style
An extreme close-up, the camera fixed as a perfect dew droplet swells on the petal’s edge, reflecting the entire forgotten garden within its shimmering surface. Cartoon style

👉 This way:

The static prompts define the shot.

The video prompts animate them with motion + emotion.

Each feels like a clip in a film sequence, not just an illustration.

nodes.title: INSTRUCTIONS
widgets_values:
INSTRUCTIONS TO FOLLOW (FINAL Version – Adapted for “Next Scene” Prompts)
Objective

From the provided text, title, author, and style, generate a sequence of text prompts intended to create an evolving storyboard of distinct static images.
Each prompt must feel like a cinematic shot, composed like a movie frame, with strong emphasis on camera perspective, composition, and atmosphere.
Strict adherence to all rules is paramount.

Input Format

You will receive five components as input:

TITLE

AUTHOR

POEM (full text)

LINE COUNT (explicit number of lines)

STYLE (requested by the user)

Step 1: Internal Reflection (no output)

Analyze Author and Title: Understand themes and artistic tone.

Read for Deeper Meaning: Extract emotions, metaphors, atmosphere.

Develop Cinematic Vision: Imagine the poem as a storyboarded film sequence.

This reflection is not written in the output.

Step 2: Prompt Generation (output)
A. The Global Prompt (first line)

Must begin with the user-defined style.

A richly descriptive master shot that represents the entire scene globally.

It must gather all key elements that will later appear in the sequence.

It must be on one single line.

B. The Modification Prompts (following lines)

Mandatory Structure:

Each must begin with “Next Scene”.

Each must briefly re-establish key existing elements from the previous frame.

Each must introduce both:

a cinematic camera change (shot, angle, framing), and

a new narrative or atmospheric change inspired by the corresponding poem line.

Each must be one direct sentence in natural language.

Each must end with the given style.

Rule of Quantity

Generate exactly one “Next Scene” prompt for EVERY line of the poem.

The total number of prompts in the output = (LINE COUNT + 1).

Example: If a poem has 10 lines, you must output 11 prompts (1 Global + 10 Next Scene).

Formatting Rules

A single line break must separate each prompt.

No double breaks or empty lines.

Clean, continuous list format.

Extended Example (Poem of 10 lines → 11 prompts)

Global Prompt (first line) + Next Scene Prompts:

In a realistic style, a wide establishing shot of an ancient stone bridge spanning a misty river at dawn, with a solitary traveler standing at its center, holding a lantern, foreshadowing the journey ahead. Realistic style
Next Scene: A medium shot from the riverbank, showing the traveler still holding the lantern on the bridge, as the mist thickens and the far end of the bridge fades from sight. Realistic style
Next Scene: A low-angle view from the water, revealing the underside of the bridge and the traveler silhouetted above, as ripples spread across the river. Realistic style
Next Scene: An over-the-shoulder shot behind the traveler, showing the lantern glow pushing faint shadows into the mist. Realistic style
Next Scene: A close-up of the traveler’s hand gripping the lantern, as the flame flickers and sparks rise into the damp air. Realistic style
Next Scene: A wide shot from the opposite bank, showing the bridge with the traveler at its center, as dark birds circle overhead in the pale sky. Realistic style
Next Scene: A high-angle shot above the bridge, showing the lantern’s glow reflected faintly in the rippling water. Realistic style
Next Scene: A tracking shot moving along the bridge, showing the traveler advancing slowly as mist swirls around their path. Realistic style
Next Scene: An extreme close-up of the traveler’s face, droplets of mist clinging to the skin as determination fills their eyes. Realistic style
Next Scene: A wide downstream shot, the bridge fading into fog, with the lantern glow shining like a star. Realistic style
Next Scene: A panoramic view of the valley, the bridge and river beneath dawn light, with the traveler a small glowing figure against the vast horizon. Realistic style



RESPECT THIS PROPERLY
